  <p>R3X contextual districts, mapped extensively in lower-density neighborhoods, such as Forest Hills in Queens and
    Princeâ€™s Bay and Westerleigh in Staten Island, permit only one- and two-family <a target="_blank"
      href="https://www.nyc.gov/site/planning/zoning/glossary.page#detached_building" class="glossary">detached</a>
    homes on lots that must be at least 35 feet wide.</p>
  <p>The 0.5 <a target="_blank" href="https://www.nyc.gov/site/planning/zoning/glossary.page#floor"
      class="glossary">floor area ratio</a> (FAR) in R3X districts may be increased by an <a target="_blank"
      href="https://www.nyc.gov/site/planning/zoning/glossary.page#attic_allowance" class="glossary">attic allowance</a>
    of up to 20% for the inclusion of space beneath a pitched roof. The <a target="_blank"
      href="https://www.nyc.gov/site/planning/zoning/glossary.page#perimeter" class="glossary">perimeter wall</a> may
    rise to 21 feet before sloping or being set back to a maximum building height of 35 feet. The amount of required <a
      target="_blank" href="https://www.nyc.gov/site/planning/zoning/glossary.page#open_space" class="glossary">open
      space</a> on a lot is governed by <a target="_blank"
      href="https://www.nyc.gov/site/planning/zoning/glossary.page#yard" class="glossary">yard</a> requirements. Two
    side yards that total at least 10 feet are required and there must be a minimum distance of eight feet between
    houses on adjacent lots. The front yard of a new home must be at least 10 feet deep and, to promote a unified
    streetscape, it must be at least as deep as an adjacent front yard but need not exceed a depth of 20 feet. An
    in-house garage is permitted within the building provided the driveway is at least 18 feet deep. One off-street
    parking space is required for each dwelling unit.</p>
